the very center of the picture,

00:34:49.340 --> 00:34:52.000
because his family would
occasionally spend a week there

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:56.050
in the summer, again, to get out
of the sweltering heat of the city.

00:34:56.050 --> 00:35:02.380
It's so moving to find photographs
of one family in the album

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:05.820
of another family, but it's
happening to us more and more.

00:35:05.820 --> 00:35:08.650
So I was looking through the
photographs of the Alonso family

00:35:08.650 --> 00:35:11.150
and came across this
photo of my grandfather

00:35:11.150 --> 00:35:14.060
and grandmother and parents.

00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:19.280
Some photographs, like this,
have almost allegorical value

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:22.770
because this is a family
of Sevillanos who went

00:35:22.770 --> 00:35:25.180
to Hawaii and then to California.

00:35:25.180 --> 00:35:28.200 position:56%
And it's almost as if their stringed
instruments were allegorically

00:35:28.200 --> 00:35:29.670
telling the story [laughter].

00:35:29.670 --> 00:35:33.200
They've got the Spanish
guitar, the Hawaiian ukulele

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:35.500
and the American banjo [laughter].

00:35:38.670 --> 00:35:42.380
The next chapter is about the
organizations that they formed.

00:35:42.380 --> 00:35:45.890
Like all other immigrants who came
to the U.S. before the New Deal,

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:49.240
the Spaniards landed in a country
where there was no safety net,

00:35:49.240 --> 00:35:52.310
no ready-made welfare state,
there was no social security,

00:35:52.310 --> 00:35:55.120
no unemployment insurance,
no medical insurance.

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:58.460
And these Spaniards all over the
U.S. responded to this situation

00:35:58.460 --> 00:36:02.570
with an astounding spirit of
entrepreneurship and solidarity,

00:36:02.570 --> 00:36:05.560
forming all manners of
clubs and organizations

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:07.380
to help them care for one another.

00:36:07.380 --> 00:36:09.490
So this is a picnic,
this is one-fourth

00:36:09.490 --> 00:36:13.450
of a vast panoramic picture
of the Spanish community

00:36:13.450 --> 00:36:16.680
in Cleveland, Ohio, 1930.

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:24.370 position:56%
Another Saint Louis picture, this is
the -- the building still exists --

00:36:24.370 --> 00:36:29.520
this is the Sociedad Espanola
of Saint Louis, Missouri.

00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:32.480
They brought with them a game,
El Hoyo Del La Jave [phonetic]

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:36.780
which many Spaniards probably don't
know because it's very peculiar

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:39.050
to the area of Asturias
where they're from.

00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:41.210
But the guy in the front
is holding this pole

00:36:41.210 --> 00:36:44.430
with these aspas [phonetic]
and the game consisted

00:36:44.430 --> 00:36:47.640
of throwing these metal discs
from a certain distance and trying

00:36:47.640 --> 00:36:53.250
to hit those blades on that stick.

00:36:53.250 --> 00:36:56.820
There's still a league of La Jave
in Saint Louis, I've been told,

00:36:56.820 --> 00:37:04.990
and you can still go there and play
and probably gamble, I would guess.

00:37:04.990 --> 00:37:10.390 position:56%
Canton, Ohio, I mentioned it before,
had a very active social club.

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:14.870 position:56%
And Canton is unusual because, as I
mentioned before, one of the streams

00:37:14.870 --> 00:37:18.920 position:56%
of immigrants are the Asturianos
who come following the zinc circuit.

00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:21.860
The other stream are on
the [inaudible] who come

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:25.330
from the Rio Tinto, Rio Tinto mines

00:37:25.330 --> 00:37:27.340
in the province of
Nuerva [phonetic].

00:37:27.340 --> 00:37:30.890 position:56%
There's a lot of labor unrest and
people are being laid off their jobs

00:37:30.890 --> 00:37:32.700
in the teens and into the twenties.

00:37:32.700 --> 00:37:36.820
And there's a mini diaspara of
[inaudible] from the province

00:37:36.820 --> 00:37:40.530
of Huelva to Canton where
they mix with the Spaniards.

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:45.120
And so their annual picnics have
both flamenco guitar and gaita.

00:37:45.120 --> 00:37:48.040
And we've documented cases
of Asturian boys who learned

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:52.560
to become flamenco musicians
because of this mingling,

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:56.650
something that is not likely
to happen on the peninsula.

00:37:56.650 --> 00:38:00.760
This is the Centro Vasco
Americano in New York.

00:38:00.760 --> 00:38:03.090
The picture's taken
in the club's fronton.

00:38:03.090 --> 00:38:08.830
They had an indoor handball
jai alai court from 1930.

00:38:11.180 --> 00:38:18.210
Soccer teams, again from
Saint Louis, [inaudible] 1934.

00:38:18.210 --> 00:38:24.220
And in other places
like Tampa, Florida,

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:27.420
where there was more
contact with the Cuban world,

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:31.010 position:56%
baseball took precedence over soccer

00:38:31.010 --> 00:38:33.230
and baseball was bigger
in Tampa than soccer.

00:38:33.230 --> 00:38:36.580
And the Centro Asturiano
had its own ball team.

00:38:36.580 --> 00:38:41.450
Some very famous professional
baseball players

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:44.330
of Spanish descent emerged.

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:47.750
I'll mention a couple
in my conclusion.

00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:50.260
Families conserved
a lot of documents,

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:53.800
