00:39:29.190 --> 00:39:32.780
a cigar workers' strike in 1920.

00:39:34.680 --> 00:39:41.060
The Spanish Civil War, by the time
the war breaks out in July of 1936,

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:44.130
the colonies of Spanish immigrants
all over the United States are

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:47.940
at their peak in terms of
numbers and cohesiveness.

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:52.660
So they've been arriving
steadily from 1898 to 1920, 22,

00:39:52.660 --> 00:39:55.060
when those quota laws
are put in place

00:39:55.060 --> 00:39:57.130
and it becomes much
harder to get in.

00:39:57.130 --> 00:40:01.360
But they still get, continue to
get it in, lest everyone think

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:05.160
that they were all legal, uh-unh.

00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:12.680
And, actually, the Cuba,
Tampa entry was a lot easier

00:40:12.680 --> 00:40:15.760
than Ellis Island for, after
the quota laws were enacted

00:40:15.760 --> 00:40:17.240
for Spaniards.

00:40:17.240 --> 00:40:22.390
So the community is at
its highest point in terms

00:40:22.390 --> 00:40:24.180
of cohesiveness and numbers.

00:40:24.180 --> 00:40:27.660
If you think about it, the
Great Depression forced them

00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:29.440
into helping each other.

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:32.140
So those organizations that they
founded, maybe at the beginning,

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:36.230
they were supporting our cultural
organizations but, after 1929,

00:40:36.230 --> 00:40:39.890
they become mutual aid
societies or burial societies.

00:40:39.890 --> 00:40:42.560
There's a real need for the
community to help each other.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:47.140 position:56%
So throughout the early 1930s, those
clubs get stronger and stronger and,

00:40:47.140 --> 00:40:51.270
when the war breaks out in
Spain in 1936, the vast majority

00:40:51.270 --> 00:40:54.710
of these working class
immigrants were pro-Republican.

00:40:54.710 --> 00:40:58.640
And most of their clubs, in
fact, I can't find many examples

00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:04.500
of any clubs that were
pro-Insurgents, pro-Franco, right.

00:41:04.500 --> 00:41:06.550
So the vast majority of the
immigrants, and almost all

00:41:06.550 --> 00:41:12.520 position:56%
of their organizations, turned their
efforts to the raising supply --

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:15.750
raising support for
the loyalist cause.

00:41:15.750 --> 00:41:21.150
And the family albums are
full of these documents.

00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:26.820
Stunning pictures like this
on 14th Street, outside of --

00:41:26.820 --> 00:41:30.780
it was actually they're picketing
a Spanish business which is proof

00:41:30.780 --> 00:41:34.040
that there were Spaniards
who were pro-Franco.

00:41:34.040 --> 00:41:35.340
That was Casa Moneo,

00:41:35.340 --> 00:41:38.650
a very important grocery
store on 14th Street.

00:41:38.650 --> 00:41:41.640
But this is, it looks
like a newspaper picture,

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:44.340
but it's actually -- the person
who showed me this says, "Oh,

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:48.810
that's my Aunt Zazi", so this
is a family picture [laughter].

00:41:52.430 --> 00:41:56.460
Fantastic portraits like this one,

00:41:56.460 --> 00:42:02.270
[foreign language spoken]
Canton, Ohio, 1937.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:12.360
Assorted pictures from the
album of a family in New Jersey.

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:16.370
These are children in Tampa,
Florida dressed up like milicianas

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:19.730
with the popular front salute.

00:42:19.730 --> 00:42:22.850
A mass meeting in Manhattan's
Center.

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:29.260
A family in Canton, Ohio has
preserved all of the programs,

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:33.210
since the 1930s, of the annual
Spanish Picnic organized

00:42:33.210 --> 00:42:36.500 position:56%
by the Spanish colonies of the area.

00:42:36.500 --> 00:42:39.620
In this juxtaposition of
2 of the program covers,

00:42:39.620 --> 00:42:42.890
the one on the left is from
1937, and the one on the right is

00:42:42.890 --> 00:42:47.040
from 1946, I think this
juxtaposition provides a perfect

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:51.610
illustration of the process I'm
trying to document and describe

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:55.750
in which the Spanish Civil
War marks a point of no return

00:42:55.750 --> 00:42:59.490
for the immigrants in the U.S.
The language and the design

00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:03.420
of these 2 covers shows that
something catastrophic has occurred

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:06.050
between 1 cover and
the other, right.

00:43:06.050 --> 00:43:07.820
From a Spanish speaking community

00:43:07.820 --> 00:43:13.280 position:56%
on the left still looking back
towards Spain, still living in Spain

00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:17.770
in some ways, still deeply involved
in the affairs of the old country.

00:43:17.770 --> 00:43:23.530
In 9 years, we move to a community
that's English speaking and that,

00:43:23.530 --> 00:43:27.030
this very forward looking
American family which seems well

00:43:27.030 --> 00:43:29.210
on its way to assimilation.

00:43:29.210 --> 00:43:34.090
So I think that this is a perfect
example of how, in our research,

00:43:34.090 --> 00:43:38.640 position:56%
we've learned that the Spanish Civil
War was really the point where most

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:41.140
of these folks realized that,
if they dreamt about going back,

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:46.330
it wasn't going to happen, or it
certainly wasn't going to be easy.

00:43:46.330 --> 00:43:49.550
I'll start wrapping up.

00:43:49.550 --> 00:43:51.270
They were here to stay.

00:43:51.270 --> 00:43:55.320
One of our standard questions,
when we interview the descendants

00:43:55.320 --> 00:43:58.530
of immigrants, is, if their
parents or grandparents had come

00:43:58.530 --> 00:44:02.220
to the U.S. knowing that they
would permanently stay here,

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:06.590
or if they had come hoping to make
some money and return to Spain.

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:11.180
And our informants, often, respond
with firmness, sometimes mixed

00:44:11.180 --> 00:44:14.220
with surprise, almost
annoyance at the question.

00:44:14.220 --> 00:44:17.930
Oh, no, they came here because
they wanted to become American.

00:44:17.930 --> 00:44:21.620
It's kind of the standard line
that we get from descendants

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:25.410
of immigrants which
is really not true

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:27.620
and has never historically
been true of any immigrant

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:30.340
that ever left any country,
any time in the history

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:32.710
of immigration [laughter].

00:44:32.710 --> 00:44:36.560
And those same people who, without
thinking about it, say, "Oh, no,

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:40.350
they came knowing that they would
become Americans", they then start

00:44:40.350 --> 00:44:42.380
to tell us stories
and, in some cases,

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:44.950
they share their archives with us.

00:44:44.950 --> 00:44:47.310
In many cases, those archives
have letters in Spanish

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:49.010
that they haven't read,
or can't read,

00:44:49.010 --> 00:44:50.850
because they don't have Spanish.

00:44:50.850 --> 00:44:53.100
And it's always a much
more complicated picture

00:44:53.100 --> 00:44:56.950
and there's almost always
a burning desire to,

00:44:56.950 --> 00:45:00.350
at some point, go back to Spain.

00:45:00.350 --> 00:45:04.680
The Spanish Civil War is what
really kind of shuts that door.

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:06.760
And we find this in
family after family.

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:12.650
It's really only then that
that dream is put aside or,

00:45:12.650 --> 00:45:14.950
at least, postponed.

00:45:14.950 --> 00:45:18.220
Those same families that say,
"Oh, no, our parents came

00:45:18.220 --> 00:45:22.560
to become Americans", then we go
through the archive and we come

00:45:22.560 --> 00:45:26.130
across the Certificates
of Naturalization

00:45:26.130 --> 00:45:30.320
